229
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:36,000
I can just say, hey, this bot army attack I'm launching, it's actually very low entropy.

230
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:37,000
It's pure poetry.

231
00:13:37,420 --> 00:13:39,600
That is the most obvious objection for sure.

232
00:13:40,180 --> 00:13:43,620
And the paper solves it with a mechanism called staking and slashing.

233
00:13:43,780 --> 00:13:45,420
Which sounds kind of violent.

234
00:13:45,620 --> 00:13:46,880
It's financial violence, really.

235
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:52,360
To participate in the plenum hub, to write anything to the manifold, you must post a stake,

236
00:13:52,740 --> 00:13:53,200
a bond.

237
00:13:53,300 --> 00:13:54,180
It could be crypto tokens.

238
00:13:54,260 --> 00:13:55,400
It could be reputation points.

239
00:13:55,480 --> 00:13:57,380
But it must be something of real value.

240
00:13:57,480 --> 00:13:57,640
Yeah.

241
00:13:57,640 --> 00:14:02,500
If you declare a low entropy budget, but the network analyzes your content and realizes

242
00:14:02,500 --> 00:14:08,620
it is actually high entropy noise like spam, lies, or just incoherence, your stake is slashed.

243
00:14:08,780 --> 00:14:09,660
You just lose your deposit.

244
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:11,200
You lose it instantly.

245
00:14:12,020 --> 00:14:13,880
This completely flips the economics.

246
00:14:14,560 --> 00:14:16,840
Suddenly, being a troll isn't free anymore.

247
00:14:17,240 --> 00:14:19,160
It becomes prohibitively expensive.

248
00:14:19,940 --> 00:14:23,580
If you want to pollute the information stream, you have to pay for the cleanup.

249
00:14:24,060 --> 00:14:24,680
I really like that.

250
00:14:24,740 --> 00:14:27,020
It's basically a carbon tax for digital pollution.

251
00:14:27,660 --> 00:14:27,940
Exactly.

252
00:14:28,460 --> 00:14:30,240
It forces thermodynamic accountability.

253
00:14:30,900 --> 00:14:33,160
You have to put real skin in the game if you want to speak.

254
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:37,340
Now, this does bring up a concern for me, and I'm sure for anyone listening.

255
00:14:37,660 --> 00:14:39,540
Does this mean only rich people can post?

256
00:14:40,020 --> 00:14:44,320
If I have to post a bond to tweet, isn't that just killing free speech for people who don't

257
00:14:44,320 --> 00:14:44,980
have resources?

258
00:14:45,360 --> 00:14:46,860
The paper addresses this directly.

259
00:14:47,400 --> 00:14:49,100
The cost isn't necessarily dollars.

260
00:14:49,220 --> 00:14:50,820
It's value within the network.

261
00:14:50,820 --> 00:14:55,880
If you have a long history of high-fidelity, truthful contributions, your reputation stake

262
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:56,560
grows naturally.

263
00:14:56,680 --> 00:14:58,200
You can spend that reputation to post.

264
00:14:58,900 --> 00:15:02,460
But if you are a brand-new, completely anonymous account, yes, the barrier is higher.

265
00:15:02,740 --> 00:15:04,680
You can't just spin up a million bots in a basement.

266
00:15:04,960 --> 00:15:10,140
You have to stake them all, which makes botnets economically unviable right out of the gate.

267
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:15,180
So it kills the bots, but it might make it a bit harder for a whistleblower or a brand-new

268
00:15:15,180 --> 00:15:17,280
voice to break in initially.

269
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:18,380
Potentially, yes.

270
00:15:18,940 --> 00:15:22,000
It heavily prioritizes stability over virality.

271
00:15:22,560 --> 00:15:25,880
It is a conservative system in the physics sense of the word.

272
00:15:26,320 --> 00:15:29,180
It actively resists rapid, chaotic fluctuations.

273
00:15:29,500 --> 00:15:32,120
Let's talk about the content itself in this new system.

274
00:15:32,460 --> 00:15:35,780
Because we aren't just posting JPEGs or text files anymore.

275
00:15:35,780 --> 00:15:37,960
We are posting semantic spheres.

276
00:15:38,740 --> 00:15:41,640
This is hands down my favorite technical detail in the whole paper.

277
00:15:42,300 --> 00:15:44,540
A semantic sphere is a formal data object.

278
00:15:45,020 --> 00:15:47,240
And it contains four very specific things.

279
00:15:47,780 --> 00:15:51,060
One, identity, which is a cryptographic hash of who you are.

280
00:15:51,340 --> 00:15:53,520
Two, payload the actual content itself.

281
00:15:53,880 --> 00:15:56,120
Three, entropy that disorder score we just discussed.

282
00:15:56,240 --> 00:15:57,580
And the fourth one is provenance.

283
00:15:57,960 --> 00:16:00,300
Provenance is the absolute game-changer here.

284
00:16:00,720 --> 00:16:04,640
Currently, you can take a screenshot of a headline, crop out the date, crop out the author, and

285
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:06,060
just post it to rage-bait people.

286
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:07,520
That is called context-dripping.

287
00:16:07,760 --> 00:16:09,020
We see it literally every day.

288
00:16:09,100 --> 00:16:10,240
Look what this politician said.

289
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:14,040
But they actually said it 10 years ago as a joke in a totally different context.

290
00:16:14,440 --> 00:16:18,420
In PlenumHub, a semantic sphere must contain its provenance graph.

291
00:16:18,860 --> 00:16:22,040
It must cryptographically link all the way back to its source.

292
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:27,980
If you try to post an orphan clip, a clip with the context severed from it, the system just

293
00:16:27,980 --> 00:16:28,600
rejects it.

294
00:16:29,280 --> 00:16:29,960
It's a type error.

295
00:16:30,280 --> 00:16:33,540
So it effectively bans out of context as a category of content.

296
00:16:33,540 --> 00:16:36,700
It demands what the paper calls media-quine closure.

297
00:16:37,560 --> 00:16:41,660
A quine, in computer science, is a program that contains its own source code.

298
00:16:42,760 --> 00:16:46,300
A media-quine is a piece of media that contains its own entire context.

299
00:16:46,940 --> 00:16:51,040
You cannot consume the snippet without dragging the whole history of the information with it.

300
00:16:51,100 --> 00:16:53,220
This connects directly to sheaf theory, right?

301
00:16:53,460 --> 00:16:56,160
Which, I admit, I had to read like three times to grasp.

302
00:16:56,300 --> 00:16:57,500
It's about gluing things together.

303
00:16:57,600 --> 00:16:58,760
It's about truth consistency.

304
00:16:58,760 --> 00:17:02,480
Imagine I have a map of New York, and you have a map of New Jersey.

305
00:17:02,860 --> 00:17:06,820
If we put them side-by-side on a table, the roads at the border should line up perfectly.

306
00:17:07,100 --> 00:17:07,960
They should glue together.

307
00:17:08,280 --> 00:17:12,700
If my road ends at the river, and your road starts 10 miles north, our maps don't glue.

308
00:17:13,100 --> 00:17:14,720
One of us is objectively wrong.

309
00:17:14,720 --> 00:17:15,280
Right.

310
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:22,340
Sheaf theory is the rigorous math of ensuring local data glues into a consistent global whole.

311
00:17:23,040 --> 00:17:32,600
In information terms, if I post a clip saying the mayor hates puppies, and the full original video shows the mayor playing happily with the puppy, those two pieces of data do not glue.

312
00:17:33,100 --> 00:17:34,200
There is a sheaf violation.

313
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:41,080
So the system actually detects that the local truth, the short clip, contradicts the global truth of the full video.

314
00:17:41,320 --> 00:17:42,460
And it creates resistance.

315
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:45,400
It degrades the value of your post immediately.

316
00:17:45,980 --> 00:17:48,740
Specifically, it degrades the texture crystal value.

317
00:17:48,820 --> 00:17:49,760
Okay, perfect segue.

318
00:17:50,060 --> 00:17:50,840
Texture crystal.

319
00:17:51,220 --> 00:17:53,180
We are entering the economy section now.

320
00:17:53,280 --> 00:17:54,040
This is segment three.

321
00:17:54,240 --> 00:17:56,940
The paper proposes completely replacing likes with crystals.

322
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:58,800
Now, I have to be totally honest with you.

323
00:17:58,860 --> 00:18:02,920
When I first read the word crystals in the outline, I thought, okay, we've gone full hippie here.

324
00:18:02,920 --> 00:18:09,220
It does sound a bit new age on the surface, but it's actually hardcore condensed matter physics applied directly to economics.

325
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:14,500
The ultimate goal is to move from an attention economy to a structure economy.

326
00:18:14,880 --> 00:18:16,400
What is the fundamental difference there?

327
00:18:16,700 --> 00:18:23,400
In an attention economy, you get paid either in dopamine likes or actual ad revenue just for making people look.

328
00:18:23,900 --> 00:18:25,460
It doesn't matter why they look at all.

329
00:18:25,860 --> 00:18:27,560
A horrific car crash gets looks.

330
00:18:28,020 --> 00:18:30,240
A genius scientific breakthrough gets looks.

331
00:18:30,880 --> 00:18:32,420
They are priced exactly the same.

332
00:18:32,420 --> 00:18:35,280
Actually, the car crash usually is a lot better.

333
00:18:35,560 --> 00:18:36,400
Sadly correct.

334
00:18:36,880 --> 00:18:41,600
In a structure economy, you get paid for building meaning, for reducing entropy.

335
00:18:42,360 --> 00:18:46,980
The paper proposes two new currencies for this, texture crystals and time crystals.

336
00:18:47,240 --> 00:18:48,380
Let's start with texture crystals.

337
00:18:48,640 --> 00:18:50,260
The text says this measures novelty.

338
00:18:50,540 --> 00:18:51,880
But not just random newness.

339
00:18:52,300 --> 00:18:54,060
It measures allocative efficiency.

340
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:57,500
The underlying formula involves something called mutual information.

341
00:18:57,740 --> 00:19:01,100
Basically, it asks the network, is this post redundant?

342
00:19:01,100 --> 00:19:03,880
Give me a real world example of how that works.

343
00:19:04,020 --> 00:19:04,220
Okay.

344
00:19:04,620 --> 00:19:06,260
Let's say a major news event happens.

345
00:19:06,740 --> 00:19:09,380
A famous celebrity falls down the stairs on live TV.

346
00:19:09,560 --> 00:19:10,600
A classic internet moment.

347
00:19:10,880 --> 00:19:15,340
Within 10 minutes, there are 50,000 tweets making the exact same pun about the fall.

348
00:19:15,480 --> 00:19:16,640
He really fell for her.

349
00:19:16,840 --> 00:19:17,780
Times 50,000.

350
00:19:17,780 --> 00:19:18,380
Exactly.

351
00:19:18,380 --> 00:19:22,800
In the current economy, all 50,000 of those people might get a few likes.

352
00:19:23,200 --> 00:19:24,480
They all get a tiny hit of dopamine.

353
00:19:25,420 --> 00:19:30,340
In the crystal economy, the very first person to make the joke creates a texture crystal.

354
00:19:31,100 --> 00:19:33,380
They add a genuinely new information to the manifold.

355
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:36,260
The second person adds very little new info.

356
00:19:36,800 --> 00:19:40,200
By the time you get to the 50,000th person, they add zero new information.

357
00:19:40,780 --> 00:19:43,820
Their texture crystal yield is mathematically zero.

358
00:19:43,820 --> 00:19:44,680
Oh, wow.

359
00:19:44,860 --> 00:19:47,500
So copy-paste culture is demonetized instantly.

360
00:19:47,960 --> 00:19:49,960
It ruthlessly penalizes redundancy.

361
00:19:50,640 --> 00:19:54,480
If you are just echoing the noise that's already there, you get absolutely nothing.

362
00:19:54,900 --> 00:20:01,220
You are only rewarded for heterogeneity, for adding a perspective or a fact that isn't already present in the space.

363
00:20:01,380 --> 00:20:03,580
That would silence so much of the modern internet.

364
00:20:03,640 --> 00:20:04,580
It would silence the echo.

365
00:20:04,720 --> 00:20:05,680
That's the entire point.

366
00:20:05,940 --> 00:20:09,220
It demands that you say something genuinely unique or you say nothing at all.

367
00:20:09,380 --> 00:20:09,640
Okay.

368
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:10,660
That makes sense for texture.

369
00:20:10,840 --> 00:20:11,700
What about time crystals?

370
00:20:11,700 --> 00:20:14,360
Time crystals measure provenance-weighted persistence.

371
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:17,920
This addresses the flash-in-the-pan problem of viral media.

372
00:20:18,380 --> 00:20:22,440
You mean the viral hit that everyone obsesses over and then completely forgets in 24 hours?

373
00:20:22,660 --> 00:20:22,880
Right.

374
00:20:23,320 --> 00:20:27,680
Currently, if you go viral today, you get a massive follower boost that lasts forever.

375
00:20:28,200 --> 00:20:30,900
You can basically coast on that past glory for years.

376
00:20:31,860 --> 00:20:33,840
Time crystals introduce a decay factor.

377
00:20:34,540 --> 00:20:36,800
The math is an exponential decay function.

378
00:20:36,940 --> 00:20:39,840
So my influence basically rots over time.

379
00:20:39,840 --> 00:20:43,820
Your influence rots unless your work is structurally load-bearing.

380
00:20:44,140 --> 00:20:46,900
What does structurally load-bearing mean in this context?

381
00:20:47,160 --> 00:20:49,680
It means other people are actively building on top of it.

382
00:20:49,940 --> 00:21:00,780
If you wrote an incredibly insightful thread three years ago and people are still citing it today, still linking to it, still using it as the foundation for their own new ideas, then the system refreshes your time crystals.

383
00:21:01,460 --> 00:21:05,300
You are providing ongoing structural integrity to the information manifold.

384
00:21:05,300 --> 00:21:10,780
So the influencer of the future isn't the person who stands on a stage and screams the loudest.

385
00:21:11,060 --> 00:21:14,880
It's the person who lays the strongest foundation that everyone else stands on.

386
00:21:14,980 --> 00:21:15,300
Exactly.

387
00:21:15,700 --> 00:21:18,620
It moves status from your visibility to actual support.

388
00:21:19,260 --> 00:21:19,760
Are you a pillar?

389
00:21:20,460 --> 00:21:21,760
Or are you just decoration?

390
00:21:22,240 --> 00:21:24,500
If you are a pillar, you accrue long-term value.

391
00:21:24,860 --> 00:21:27,280
If you are a decoration, you decay and fade away.

392
00:21:27,280 --> 00:21:33,260
I really love the idea of the librarian or the archivist becoming the ultimate internet power user.

393
00:21:33,900 --> 00:21:38,020
The person who quietly organizes and connects things gets the most status.

394
00:21:38,720 --> 00:21:40,200
It absolutely favors the synthesizer.

395
00:21:40,400 --> 00:21:41,260
It favors the historian.

396
00:21:41,620 --> 00:21:41,720
Yeah.

397
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:44,560
And it heavily penalizes the hot take artist.

398
00:21:44,760 --> 00:21:47,100
It's a complete inversion of our current values.

399
00:21:47,260 --> 00:21:48,220
But let's zoom out a bit.

400
00:21:48,560 --> 00:21:55,140
Because the paper argues that this shift from engagement to structure is actually part of a much larger evolutionary trend.

401
00:21:55,140 --> 00:21:58,140
This brings us to segment four, chippification.

402
00:21:58,780 --> 00:21:59,220
Chippification.

403
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:02,620
It's a really fun word for a very deep historical process.

404
00:22:02,760 --> 00:22:02,860
Right.

405
00:22:03,160 --> 00:22:07,660
Flyxion argues that physical systems inevitably evolve into abstract logical systems.

406
00:22:07,880 --> 00:22:09,880
Use the factory example in the text.

407
00:22:10,040 --> 00:22:10,240
Right.

408
00:22:10,340 --> 00:22:11,660
Think about the Industrial Revolution.

409
00:22:12,140 --> 00:22:14,080
A factory was a massive physical beast.

410
00:22:14,260 --> 00:22:16,460
Steam engines, huge gears, belts, pulleys.

411
00:22:16,860 --> 00:22:20,060
If you wanted to change the logic of a factory, say, change the order of assembly,

412
00:22:20,440 --> 00:22:22,920
you had to physically unbolt and move a two-ton machine.

413
00:22:22,920 --> 00:22:25,480
You had to get a massive wrench and a crew of guys.

414
00:22:25,960 --> 00:22:26,620
Then came electricity.

415
00:22:27,040 --> 00:22:28,120
Then electrical relays.

416
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:30,060
Then silicon logic gates.

417
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:37,540
Now, that entire factory's operational logic is encoded on a tiny silicon chick, a PLC controller.

418
00:22:37,960 --> 00:22:39,320
The factory is now software.

419
00:22:39,800 --> 00:22:42,640
The physical machines that were just peripherals plugged into the code.

420
00:22:42,840 --> 00:22:45,760
And the example that really clicked for me was the Nintendo cartridge.

421
00:22:46,060 --> 00:22:46,340
Yes.

422
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:47,300
It's a perfect analogy.

423
00:22:47,720 --> 00:22:50,000
Think of an old arcade cabinet, like Donkey Kong.

424
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:53,080
It was a physical mess of wires and custom circuit boards.

425
00:22:53,500 --> 00:22:55,120
A literal physical labyrinth.

426
00:22:55,600 --> 00:23:00,400
Then Nintendo came along and condensed all that complex logic into a small plastic cartridge.

427
00:23:00,880 --> 00:23:02,460
And now we have software emulators.

428
00:23:02,700 --> 00:23:03,740
The plastic is gone.

429
00:23:03,900 --> 00:23:04,860
The silicon is gone.

430
00:23:04,940 --> 00:23:08,860
But the logic of Donkey Kong exists as pure code on my laptop.

431
00:23:09,320 --> 00:23:11,480
The logic survives the physical medium.

432
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:15,160
The paper argues that everything in our world is undergoing this chipification.

433
00:23:15,660 --> 00:23:18,840
Supply chains, logistics, governance, corporate organizations.

434
00:23:18,840 --> 00:23:22,840
We are steadily turning the messy physical world into virtual machines.

435
00:23:23,180 --> 00:23:25,260
So the physical world is really just becoming the hardware.

436
00:23:25,460 --> 00:23:27,960
The real world is the software running on top of it.

437
00:23:28,400 --> 00:23:33,100
And if that's true, we need to look very closely at how software creates stability.

438
00:23:34,360 --> 00:23:37,560
Which is why the paper pivots to swarm dynamics.

439
00:23:37,900 --> 00:23:38,260
Cars.

440
00:23:38,840 --> 00:23:39,640
Autonomous cars.

441
00:23:39,940 --> 00:23:40,320
Cars.

442
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:43,940
We currently think of self-driving cars as personal chauffeurs.

443
00:23:44,340 --> 00:23:45,340
My car drives me.

444
00:23:45,340 --> 00:23:49,620
But once all cars are chippified and communicating, they aren't individuals anymore.

445
00:23:49,720 --> 00:23:50,520
They become a network.

446
00:23:51,080 --> 00:23:51,580
A swarm.

447
00:23:51,960 --> 00:23:53,520
Like a flock of starlings.

448
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:58,080
You know, you've seen those amazing videos where hundreds of thousands of birds fly in

449
00:23:58,080 --> 00:24:01,720
a massive cloud, turning instantly, never crashing into each other.

450
00:24:02,140 --> 00:24:03,840
That phenomena is called stigmergy.

451
00:24:04,220 --> 00:24:06,440
It's coordination through the environment itself.

452
00:24:07,060 --> 00:24:11,940
And the reason those birds don't crash is a specific mathematical property called the spectral

453
00:24:11,940 --> 00:24:12,300
gap.

454
00:24:12,620 --> 00:24:14,640
Okay, you're going to have to define spectral gap for me.

455
00:24:14,640 --> 00:24:19,180
It's a measure of how quickly information propagates through a network, relative to

456
00:24:19,180 --> 00:24:21,340
how quickly the network changes its physical shape.

457
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:26,920
In a flock of birds, if the lead bird turns sharply, that information ripples to the very

458
00:24:26,920 --> 00:24:29,400
back of the flock faster than the flock can collide.

459
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:30,860
The gap is open.

460
00:24:31,300 --> 00:24:32,960
Stability is automatically maintained.

461
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:34,400
And how does that apply to the internet?

462
00:24:34,960 --> 00:24:37,740
The internet currently has a collapsed spectral gap.

463
00:24:39,080 --> 00:24:42,900
Information, specifically outrage and fear, moves instantly.

464
00:24:42,900 --> 00:24:48,540
But the correction, the context, the nuanced truth moves incredibly slowly.

465
00:24:49,240 --> 00:24:54,300
Or, conversely, the herd stampedes before the accurate information can even propagate.

466
00:24:55,300 --> 00:24:57,720
We have phantom traffic jams of pure anger.

467
00:24:58,040 --> 00:25:01,640
Oh, you know those traffic jams where everyone comes to a complete stop on the highway, but

468
00:25:01,640 --> 00:25:02,380
there's no accident?

469
00:25:02,620 --> 00:25:06,080
Just someone tap their brake three miles ahead and the ripple effect stopped the whole highway?

470
00:25:06,180 --> 00:25:06,660
Exactly.

471
00:25:06,660 --> 00:25:08,680
That is a textbook stability failure.

472
00:25:09,540 --> 00:25:12,780
The paper argues that social media is currently a crashing swarm.

473
00:25:13,320 --> 00:25:17,920
We are constantly crashing into each other because we lack the geometric controls, the spectral

474
00:25:17,920 --> 00:25:20,060
gap maintenance to fly together safely.

475
00:25:20,280 --> 00:25:24,420
So Plenumub is basically trying to install air traffic control for the human hive mind.

476
00:25:24,620 --> 00:25:29,000
It's trying to give the digital swarm the exact same mathematical elegance that nature

477
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:29,780
gave the starlings.

478
00:25:30,240 --> 00:25:32,340
It's biomimicry at the base protocol level.

479
00:25:32,340 --> 00:25:34,760
That is a genuinely beautiful image.

480
00:25:35,320 --> 00:25:38,880
But before we get too carried away with the beauty of the math, we really need to talk

481
00:25:38,880 --> 00:25:40,920
about the human cost of the current system.

482
00:25:41,620 --> 00:25:44,640
This is segment five, the ethics of optimization.

483
00:25:45,380 --> 00:25:49,440
The paper uses an analogy here that I think absolutely everyone listening will understand

484
00:25:49,440 --> 00:25:51,880
immediately, the Pepsi paradigm.

485
00:25:52,140 --> 00:25:52,960
The sip test.

486
00:25:53,300 --> 00:25:55,720
This is legendary in advertising and marketing circles.

487
00:25:55,820 --> 00:25:56,860
Tell the story for us.

488
00:25:56,860 --> 00:26:02,460
So back in the day, Pepsi ran the famous Pepsi Challenge, a blind taste test in malls.

489
00:26:02,520 --> 00:26:04,380
One sip of Coke, one sip of Pepsi.

490
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:06,920
And people overwhelmingly chose Pepsi.

491
00:26:07,020 --> 00:26:07,780
Because Pepsi is sweeter.

492
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:08,340
Exactly.

493
00:26:08,640 --> 00:26:10,760
It has more sugar and a sharper citrus burst.

494
00:26:11,420 --> 00:26:14,280
In a single one ounce sip, that sweetness is delightful.

495
00:26:14,420 --> 00:26:14,860
It's a pop.

496
00:26:15,380 --> 00:26:18,260
Coke is a bit more dry, more complex, almost raisiny.

497
00:26:18,280 --> 00:26:20,240
Everybody buys a one ounce sip of soda.

498
00:26:20,340 --> 00:26:21,240
You buy a whole can.

499
00:26:21,420 --> 00:26:22,260
And that's the catch.

500
00:26:22,420 --> 00:26:23,060
That's the paradigm.

501
00:26:23,060 --> 00:26:27,180
If you have to drink a whole 12 ounce can, the extreme sweetness of Pepsi can actually

502
00:26:27,180 --> 00:26:28,200
become cloying.

503
00:26:28,540 --> 00:26:29,400
It's just too much.

504
00:26:29,920 --> 00:26:35,180
Over the longer duration of a whole can, people often prefer the more complex, drier flavor

505
00:26:35,180 --> 00:26:36,160
profile of Coke.

506
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:39,240
So the sip experience directly contradicts the can experience.

507
00:26:39,600 --> 00:26:39,900
Yes.

508
00:26:40,320 --> 00:26:44,200
And the internet we have today is entirely optimized for the sip.

509
00:26:44,360 --> 00:26:44,840
Tick tock.

510
00:26:44,940 --> 00:26:45,900
The ultimate sip machine.

511
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:46,880
15 seconds.

512
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:48,000
A massive sugar rush.

513
00:26:48,660 --> 00:26:49,440
A dopamine hit.

514
00:26:50,220 --> 00:26:50,580
Nast.

515
00:26:51,180 --> 00:26:51,580
Next.

516
00:26:51,860 --> 00:26:52,140
Next.

517
00:26:52,140 --> 00:26:54,540
But life, I mean, a human life is a can.

518
00:26:54,780 --> 00:26:56,520
Life is a long duration event.

519
00:26:57,100 --> 00:27:02,840
We are optimizing our entire digital civilization for the immediate five second sip of engagement

520
00:27:02,840 --> 00:27:08,200
and completely ignoring the fact that drinking 5,000 sips of pure syrup in a row makes you

521
00:27:08,200 --> 00:27:09,060
violently sick.

522
00:27:09,180 --> 00:27:10,380
We are structurally diabetic.

523
00:27:10,780 --> 00:27:12,540
The paper calls this temporal distortion.

524
00:27:13,440 --> 00:27:18,240
We are actively destroying long term value like our mental health, our democratic institutions,

525
00:27:18,240 --> 00:27:22,900
our basic ability to focus, to maximize short term metrics like clicks and ad impressions.

526
00:27:23,120 --> 00:27:26,640
And the platforms don't care because they operate as black box behaviorists.

527
00:27:26,760 --> 00:27:26,940
Right.

528
00:27:27,080 --> 00:27:28,120
They don't care why you click.

529
00:27:28,240 --> 00:27:28,880
They really don't.

530
00:27:29,020 --> 00:27:32,280
They don't have a variable in their code for user happiness or user fulfillment.

531
00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:34,780
They simply have a variable for time on site.

532
00:27:34,780 --> 00:27:37,060
The paper calls this a functional ontology.

533
00:27:37,060 --> 00:27:39,300
We optimize what we measure.

534
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,820
That is the golden, unbreakable rule of engineering.

535
00:27:43,300 --> 00:27:48,720
If your map of the world, your ontology only contains engagement, you will optimize for engagement,

536
00:27:48,960 --> 00:27:51,000
even if it literally burns the world down.

537
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:56,440
You literally cannot see the damage you are doing because damage isn't a column in your database.

538
00:27:56,840 --> 00:27:58,780
So PlenumHub isn't just changing the code.

539
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:02,180
It's forcing the system to measure completely new things.

540
00:28:02,340 --> 00:28:03,520
It's expanding the ontology.

541
00:28:04,020 --> 00:28:10,080
It forces the digital system to measure entropy, to measure provenance, to measure novelty.

542
00:28:10,360 --> 00:28:14,100
By forcing the system to measure them, we can finally optimize for them.

543
00:28:14,180 --> 00:28:18,220
And this leads directly to the final ethical point, the right to non-extraction.

544
00:28:18,220 --> 00:28:21,300
This is the rights-based framework that ties it all together.

545
00:28:21,960 --> 00:28:27,380
Flyxion argues that as a human being, you have a fundamental right not to be harvested for behavioral surplus.

546
00:28:27,540 --> 00:28:28,100
Harvested?

547
00:28:28,300 --> 00:28:30,440
We are back to the farming metaphor from earlier.

548
00:28:30,800 --> 00:28:31,940
We are the crop.

549
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:35,140
The current geometry of the internet is a combine harvester.

550
00:28:35,680 --> 00:28:40,260
We are just the raw material being endlessly processed into prediction models.

551
00:28:40,800 --> 00:28:43,020
The right to non-extraction says,

552
00:28:43,780 --> 00:28:44,720
I am not a resource.

553
00:28:45,120 --> 00:28:45,860
I am a traveler.

554
00:28:45,860 --> 00:28:52,300
I have a fundamental right to walk a path that doesn't inevitably slide me into a psychological meat grinder.

555
00:28:52,600 --> 00:28:53,760
That is so powerful.

556
00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:55,480
It completely shifts the burden.

557
00:28:55,700 --> 00:28:57,460
It's no longer saying, oh, I need more willpower.

558
00:28:57,520 --> 00:28:58,460
I need to put my phone away.

559
00:28:58,540 --> 00:29:01,600
It's saying, the street shouldn't be built to mug me.

560
00:29:01,980 --> 00:29:02,380
Exactly.

561
00:29:02,660 --> 00:29:04,880
The geometry should protect you, not exploit you.

562
00:29:05,060 --> 00:29:06,180
So let's bring this all home.

563
00:29:06,380 --> 00:29:07,960
We've covered a ton of ground today.

564
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:11,180
Manifolds, entropy budgets, crystal economies, swarm dynamics.

565
00:29:11,320 --> 00:29:12,460
It's a very dense paper.

566
00:29:12,460 --> 00:29:16,200
But the core mission here is simple, manufacturing stability.

567
00:29:16,580 --> 00:29:18,540
It's a rallying cry for constraint-first design.

568
00:29:18,580 --> 00:29:19,940
Which feels very counterintuitive.

569
00:29:20,100 --> 00:29:22,380
Usually when we talk about the internet, it's all about freedom.

570
00:29:23,020 --> 00:29:23,800
No rules.

571
00:29:24,600 --> 00:29:25,540
Permissionless innovation.

572
00:29:25,780 --> 00:29:27,760
But the paper asks a very provocative question.

573
00:29:27,980 --> 00:29:29,300
What actually is freedom?

574
00:29:29,520 --> 00:29:32,240
Is freedom just the total absence of rules?

575
00:29:32,420 --> 00:29:35,400
I mean, that's the classic libertarian definition we hear all the time.

576
00:29:35,400 --> 00:29:38,360
But try to build a 100-story skyscraper without rules.

577
00:29:39,080 --> 00:29:42,560
Try to build a commercial airplane without strictly obeying the laws of aerodynamics.

578
00:29:43,120 --> 00:29:43,600
You can't.

579
00:29:43,980 --> 00:29:46,480
In the physical world, we have absolute constraints.

580
00:29:47,080 --> 00:29:48,300
Gravity is non-negotiable.

581
00:29:48,820 --> 00:29:50,280
Thermodynamics is non-negotiable.

582
00:29:50,300 --> 00:29:55,820
And because those rules are so rigid, we can actually build amazing, complex things on top of them safely.

583
00:29:56,120 --> 00:29:56,580
Exactly.

584
00:29:57,020 --> 00:30:01,920
The absolute rigidity of the substrate is what allows for the incredible complexity of the creation.

585
00:30:01,920 --> 00:30:05,280
The internet, up until now, has been squishy.

586
00:30:05,860 --> 00:30:10,680
The laws change every single time a CEO changes their mind or wants to boost quarterly earnings.

587
00:30:11,240 --> 00:30:12,200
The physics are fluid.

588
00:30:12,400 --> 00:30:15,800
And because the physics are fluid, our entire society feels unstable.

589
00:30:16,120 --> 00:30:19,020
We are trying to build a global civilization on quicksand.

590
00:30:19,500 --> 00:30:24,860
The paper strongly suggests that to be truly free, to have a stable, creative, healthy digital life,

591
00:30:25,160 --> 00:30:28,700
we actually need more rigid mathematical laws baked into the substrate.

592
00:30:29,180 --> 00:30:31,560
We need a digital gravity that we can rely on.

593
00:30:31,560 --> 00:30:35,620
We need to know that the floor won't suddenly tilt just because someone wants to sell more ads.

594
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:38,040
We need a stable plenum.

595
00:30:38,200 --> 00:30:43,840
A flat, quiet, truth-seeking space where the path of least resistance is also the path of wisdom.

596
00:30:44,080 --> 00:30:46,300
That is a massive, inspiring vision.

597
00:30:46,460 --> 00:30:50,500
It really makes our current internet look like a chaotic, almost primitive prototype.

598
00:30:50,500 --> 00:30:57,880
I genuinely think history will look back on the social media era of roughly 2005 to 2025 as the Wild West.

599
00:30:58,680 --> 00:31:01,320
Dangerous, extractive, and incredibly primitive.

600
00:31:01,920 --> 00:31:05,260
This paper is the blueprint for the actual civilization that comes next.

601
00:31:05,320 --> 00:31:07,360
So here's the question for you listening right now.

602
00:31:07,440 --> 00:31:09,620
Next time you unlock your phone, just pause and ask yourself,

603
00:31:09,760 --> 00:31:11,080
am I navigating my own map?

604
00:31:11,400 --> 00:31:14,360
Or am I just sliding down a gravity well that someone else dug for me?

605
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:15,380
Check a geometry.

606
00:31:15,680 --> 00:31:16,760
Thanks for diving deep with us.

607
00:31:16,760 --> 00:31:17,520
We'll see you in the next one.

